00:02:10.861 --> 00:02:14.480
So what is this about? So a two-part

40
00:02:14.580 --> 00:02:16.700
problem statement. Okay, so first of all,

41
00:02:18.780 --> 00:02:22.640
we start from the premise that we need to measure and understand the full cancer

42
00:02:22.680 --> 00:02:24.620
experience for all patients. So what does

43
00:02:25.660 --> 00:02:29.420
that mean? Well, measure, right? We have to be able to quantify in

44
00:02:29.460 --> 00:02:32.760
some way what is happening throughout the cancer experience.

45
00:02:33.190 --> 00:02:34.280
And then understand,

46
00:02:35.240 --> 00:02:39.000
is obviously taking that data and transforming it into knowledge.

47
00:02:40.160 --> 00:02:43.840
I think as most folks in the room know, only about five to 10% of patients with

48
00:02:43.880 --> 00:02:45.950
cancer will enroll in a clinical trial.

49
00:02:46.640 --> 00:02:50.630
And even when they do, more often than not, that's just a snapshot of their full

50
00:02:50.660 --> 00:02:54.200
experience. It doesn't tell the whole story.

51
00:02:54.280 --> 00:02:57.769
So that's why we would look to real-world data, such as what Project Genie is

52
00:02:57.820 --> 00:02:58.280
looking at.

53
00:02:59.410 --> 00:03:03.060
The challenge with real-world data is that it's fragmented in time and

54
00:03:03.120 --> 00:03:03.600
space,

55
00:03:04.720 --> 00:03:08.520
and requires massive effort to take those data and make sense of

56
00:03:08.560 --> 00:03:08.820
them.

57
00:03:10.520 --> 00:03:14.180
And then, of course, the aspect of Genie that's maybe different

58
00:03:14.260 --> 00:03:18.160
than some other real-world data efforts is that it's really focused on precision

59
00:03:18.220 --> 00:03:22.130
oncology. Precision oncology has major and growing importance in

60
00:03:22.160 --> 00:03:22.810
cancer treatment.

61
00:03:24.400 --> 00:03:25.980
So that's part two of the problem statement.

62
00:03:27.260 --> 00:03:30.800
So I am a big believer in prospective trials.

63
00:03:31.500 --> 00:03:34.820
I think RCTs remain the gold standard,

64
00:03:35.700 --> 00:03:39.340
but they're very difficult to conduct for general

65
00:03:39.400 --> 00:03:43.000
cancer types, and they're especially difficult for precision

66
00:03:43.100 --> 00:03:43.880
oncology.

67
00:03:44.800 --> 00:03:48.780
So just as one example, this trial iPredict, which was published a month

68
00:03:48.820 --> 00:03:50.440
or two ago in JCO,

69
00:03:51.780 --> 00:03:55.340
took more than a decade from inception to the

70
00:03:55.380 --> 00:03:56.700
publication of the results.

71
00:03:58.660 --> 00:04:01.900
And even then, the results are not conclusive, right?

72
00:04:02.060 --> 00:04:05.620
So there's a really great editorial that goes with this trial, I encourage you to

73
00:04:05.660 --> 00:04:09.380
read it, talking about how we might be able to do RCTs in

74
00:04:09.400 --> 00:04:10.340
precision oncology.

75
00:04:11.700 --> 00:04:14.660
But I think real-world data has a real role here.

76
00:04:14.780 --> 00:04:17.421
I think another nice thing to point out about iPredict

77
00:04:18.481 --> 00:04:22.400
is that it shows that prospectively and then in the real

78
00:04:22.480 --> 00:04:26.220
world, there is a very large diversity of treatment options.

79
00:04:26.340 --> 00:04:30.300
So in this particular trial, in the fine print there, they actually used

80
00:04:30.440 --> 00:04:32.840
157 different treatment regimens

81
00:04:34.380 --> 00:04:36.740
on, I forget how many patients, but there weren't too many...

82
00:04:36.900 --> 00:04:40.800
Oh, there, 210 patients. So it gives you an idea of how broad of a

83
00:04:40.900 --> 00:04:44.760
spectrum of treatment you're going to see when you look at precision oncology.

84
00:04:46.960 --> 00:04:48.060
So just a word about

85
00:04:49.200 --> 00:04:53.020
my conceptualization of the cancer experience, which I think really

86
00:04:53.100 --> 00:04:55.820
is two parallel paths.

87
00:04:56.900 --> 00:05:00.760
And I have no timeline here, but as treatments

88
00:05:00.800 --> 00:05:04.460
get better, as prevention gets better, the timelines are extending

89
00:05:04.540 --> 00:05:07.280
from months to years and even longer.

90
00:05:08.480 --> 00:05:10.160
So we've really got two parallel paths.

91
00:05:10.260 --> 00:05:14.080
One is that early-stage curable path where you have an opportunity

92
00:05:14.160 --> 00:05:18.130
to assess risk, to diagnose early, to treat, and then

93
00:05:18.160 --> 00:05:19.969
to get into surveillance and survivorship.

94
00:05:20.680 --> 00:05:24.670
And then there's the bottom path, which is probably the one

95
00:05:24.720 --> 00:05:27.430
that more than half of the patients do end up on, which is the

96
00:05:29.500 --> 00:05:32.340
incurable path. Not to say there aren't a lot of treatment options.

97
00:05:33.480 --> 00:05:35.520
We do have transition points, right?

98
00:05:35.560 --> 00:05:39.540
So we have patients who begin on the early path and transition

99
00:05:39.720 --> 00:05:42.120
during treatment, during surveillance and survivorship.

100
00:05:43.900 --> 00:05:47.280
From our perspective, we really think about treatment.

101
00:05:47.480 --> 00:05:48.380
What does it look like?

102
00:05:49.320 --> 00:05:52.800
Does it work? Does it not work? And here I've shown a hypothetical

103
00:05:52.840 --> 00:05:56.800
example of multiple lines of therapy as time goes

104
00:05:56.880 --> 00:05:57.140
on.

105
00:05:58.200 --> 00:05:59.560
And then I think the

106
00:06:00.700 --> 00:06:04.040
very important aspect of treatment of cancer is the

107
00:06:04.100 --> 00:06:07.961
toxicity of it.So we've got acute toxicities, we've got

108
00:06:08.492 --> 00:06:12.242
short-term or medium-term sequelae of treatment, and we've got late effects.

109
00:06:12.412 --> 00:06:15.652
So you bring this all together, it's quite a complex

110
00:06:15.772 --> 00:06:17.652
longitudinal situation.

111
00:06:18.932 --> 00:06:19.132
So,

112
00:06:20.512 --> 00:06:24.192
in order to try to address this, we created a new data model, and

113
00:06:24.252 --> 00:06:27.652
maybe you will ask, I will anticipate questions. We can talk about it more.

114
00:06:28.192 --> 00:06:29.531
Why another data model?

115
00:06:30.952 --> 00:06:34.832
And it's a fair question, but I think, given this precision

116
00:06:34.992 --> 00:06:35.952
oncology domain

117
00:06:36.972 --> 00:06:38.832
and the longitudinality of it,

118
00:06:39.912 --> 00:06:43.672
we did feel that we had to develop a data model that was based on

119
00:06:44.152 --> 00:06:45.112
best principles,

120
00:06:46.052 --> 00:06:47.652
but was specific to Genie.

121
00:06:49.212 --> 00:06:52.812
We wanted to build a data model that could handle the

122
00:06:53.612 --> 00:06:57.352
manual curation processes that often happen to this very

123
00:06:57.472 --> 00:07:01.452
day, but also could transition us into the near future

124
00:07:01.612 --> 00:07:03.672
state of health

125
00:07:03.712 --> 00:07:07.432
technology-enabling curation at scale.

126
00:07:09.132 --> 00:07:12.792
So as I alluded to in the beginning, we have areas of focus that we

127
00:07:12.992 --> 00:07:13.792
have defined.

128
00:07:14.612 --> 00:07:18.272
So we have the diagnostic variables and the diagnostic

129
00:07:18.292 --> 00:07:21.572
information. We have treatment information.

130
00:07:21.872 --> 00:07:25.652
We have response and outcomes, and for those

131
00:07:25.732 --> 00:07:28.352
variables, we have both the conventional

132
00:07:30.412 --> 00:07:34.372
metric-based variables, such as is a tumor shrinking or growing, and we also

133
00:07:34.432 --> 00:07:34.732
have

134
00:07:36.272 --> 00:07:38.592
patient-focused response and outcomes.

135
00:07:39.332 --> 00:07:43.092
And that's also where toxicity comes in a little bit, and our next speaker will

136
00:07:43.392 --> 00:07:47.352
talk about that. And then we try or

137
00:07:47.432 --> 00:07:51.092
think about what social determinants of health can we capture?

138
00:07:51.272 --> 00:07:54.592
What is going to be available in the medical record to

139
00:07:54.992 --> 00:07:55.392
find?

140
00:07:56.212 --> 00:07:56.962
What is important,

141
00:07:58.112 --> 00:08:00.772
and what can we potentially gather

142
00:08:01.352 --> 00:08:05.292
from other information sources, such as census

143
00:08:05.332 --> 00:08:06.412
tract-level information?

144
00:08:10.432 --> 00:08:14.151
So, one thing we think about a lot is we can make

145
00:08:14.272 --> 00:08:17.852
specifications, but if we don't harmonize data,

146
00:08:18.692 --> 00:08:21.392
we're still going to have a big challenge when we try to do a

147
00:08:21.492 --> 00:08:24.712
cross-institutional registry such as Genie.

148
00:08:26.032 --> 00:08:29.992
And so we really think upfront about the ease or challenge

149
00:08:30.032 --> 00:08:30.992
of harmonization.

150
00:08:32.293 --> 00:08:36.192
And to that end, this is a slide from a colleague in Australia

151
00:08:36.413 --> 00:08:40.232
who works with the OHDSI group. And it just illustrates that even

152
00:08:40.293 --> 00:08:40.852
when you

153
00:08:41.952 --> 00:08:45.552
specify a standard, there can still be considerable challenges.

154
00:08:45.792 --> 00:08:49.472
So here, what you're seeing are five different institutions.

155
00:08:49.512 --> 00:08:50.472
They've been masked to

156
00:08:51.392 --> 00:08:53.512
protect the innocent and guilty.

157
00:08:54.592 --> 00:08:58.552
They all were told to standardize their medication data

158
00:08:58.562 --> 00:09:02.452
to something called RxNorm, but RxNorm has many

159
00:09:02.492 --> 00:09:04.252
different subtypes.

160
00:09:05.112 --> 00:09:07.212
And what you see is that institution D

161
00:09:08.092 --> 00:09:11.212
chose the purple subtype, which happens to be called Ingredient.

162
00:09:11.612 --> 00:09:14.072
Institution E chose something called Clinical Drug,

163
00:09:15.012 --> 00:09:18.772
but institutions A, B, and C, even internally, couldn't decide which of

164
00:09:18.832 --> 00:09:22.812
these various flavors of RxNorm they were going to choose, and they end

165
00:09:22.872 --> 00:09:26.732
up with all kinds of heterogeneity even within their institution.

166
00:09:28.012 --> 00:09:31.992
So this is a challenge. You can imagine, how is it going to take to take

167
00:09:32.052 --> 00:09:35.462
these five different institutions and get some meaningful merged,

168
00:09:35.652 --> 00:09:39.482
harmonized data out of it? So we haven't necessarily solved that challenge, but

169
00:09:39.512 --> 00:09:43.482
we've known about the challenge, and we've tried to address it

170
00:09:43.512 --> 00:09:45.072
in the specifications of our data model.

171
00:09:47.072 --> 00:09:48.712
So this is a really high-level overview.

172
00:09:48.752 --> 00:09:52.712
We ended up with over about 750 core data elements and 13

173
00:09:52.812 --> 00:09:53.872
clinical domains.

174
00:09:55.672 --> 00:09:59.072
As I mentioned earlier, what we really tried to do is look at

175
00:09:59.492 --> 00:10:02.852
what's out there, what works, what doesn't work so well,

176
00:10:03.132 --> 00:10:06.702
and pick and choose from existing standards as much as

177
00:10:06.732 --> 00:10:07.192
possible.

178
00:10:08.652 --> 00:10:12.071
Our intention is to make this data model open access.

179
00:10:14.152 --> 00:10:14.732
And so I think

180
00:10:15.872 --> 00:10:19.432
what you'll hear about today are really two demands.

181
00:10:19.552 --> 00:10:21.772
One is the specifications. So that'll be our next

182
00:10:22.852 --> 00:10:24.452
talk, and that's a critical first step.

183
00:10:24.552 --> 00:10:28.452
A shared vision, which really,

184
00:10:28.512 --> 00:10:29.962
again, goes back to

185
00:10:31.032 --> 00:10:32.012
the parent Genie group,

186
00:10:32.992 --> 00:10:36.532
is essential because that's how we're going to move this type of work forward.

187
00:10:37.232 --> 00:10:39.112
But then you'll also hear about implementation.

188
00:10:39.192 --> 00:10:41.852
So one of our speakers will talk about how is this

189
00:10:41.992 --> 00:10:45.572
actually working in their medical system.

190
00:10:46.612 --> 00:10:50.581
And it's incredibly important for us to iterate on

191
00:10:50.652 --> 00:10:54.432
that kind of work. So we're not necessarily going to get it perfect the first time

192
00:10:54.472 --> 00:10:54.692
out,

193
00:10:56.532 --> 00:11:00.432
and we're going to end up improving and also probably simplifying the data model as

194
00:11:00.472 --> 00:11:01.112
time goes on.

195
00:11:01.932 --> 00:11:05.572
We hope by the end of this session that you're inspired, that you will eagerly

196
00:11:05.612 --> 00:11:09.312
await that open access version to come out, and that you'll try to use it

197
00:11:09.732 --> 00:11:10.492
in your own system

198
00:11:11.872 --> 00:11:13.632
and you'll let us know how that's going.

199
00:11:15.152 --> 00:11:18.912
So with that, I'm going to transition to our first speaker.

