210
00:11:58.132 --> 00:12:01.612
Today, I'll just be providing a high-level overview of some of the technical

211
00:12:01.732 --> 00:12:05.132
considerations that went into the building of the model.

212
00:12:07.112 --> 00:12:10.492
I have no financial disclosures beyond being employed by the

213
00:12:10.532 --> 00:12:14.438
AACR.So the question we're always asked is,

214
00:12:14.548 --> 00:12:18.408
why a new data model? I know Dr. Warner gave some of the information

215
00:12:18.448 --> 00:12:22.208
about why we chose to do this, but it really comes down to

216
00:12:22.468 --> 00:12:25.848
two important components. One being really the

217
00:12:25.888 --> 00:12:29.468
complexity of the cancer experience and collecting

218
00:12:29.528 --> 00:12:33.068
information to provide a full clinical context about the cancer

219
00:12:33.128 --> 00:12:36.938
experience, and also the evolving nature of the

220
00:12:37.008 --> 00:12:39.228
needs for precision oncology research.

221
00:12:40.228 --> 00:12:43.888
Obviously, the field changes quite rapidly and so a model

222
00:12:43.898 --> 00:12:47.878
needs to be able to be flexible and supportive of any changes

223
00:12:47.908 --> 00:12:51.868
that are needed. So to return to this idea of the complexity of

224
00:12:51.908 --> 00:12:54.328
capturing information about the cancer experience,

225
00:12:55.468 --> 00:12:59.008
we really understand that for a given data element that we may want

226
00:12:59.068 --> 00:13:02.828
represented in the model, there is variety in both how it's

227
00:13:02.888 --> 00:13:06.248
stored within the systems, whether that's the EHR,

228
00:13:07.238 --> 00:13:10.668
the laboratory information system, their imaging system,

229
00:13:11.448 --> 00:13:15.028
perhaps the tumor registry or even research warehouses.

230
00:13:15.688 --> 00:13:19.208
But then also within that, the variety of terminologies or

231
00:13:19.268 --> 00:13:23.208
vocabularies that could be used to represent any of those

232
00:13:23.228 --> 00:13:27.128
data elements from ICD-O codes to SNOMED to

233
00:13:27.168 --> 00:13:27.968
LOINC codes.

234
00:13:28.848 --> 00:13:32.808
And as Jeremy had shared in his presentation, when we're talking

235
00:13:32.828 --> 00:13:36.498
in the context of the Genie Consortium with many different sites

236
00:13:36.568 --> 00:13:40.048
contributing data, every site may house a given

237
00:13:40.388 --> 00:13:44.358
data element in a particular location, and they may align them

238
00:13:44.388 --> 00:13:47.108
with vocabulary that differs from site to site.

239
00:13:47.228 --> 00:13:51.048
So being able to harmonize all this information to have one

240
00:13:51.088 --> 00:13:53.288
large data set is quite complicated,

241
00:13:54.468 --> 00:13:58.188
but this is a necessary goal in order to really drive precision

242
00:13:58.248 --> 00:14:01.468
oncology research needs, particularly when we think

243
00:14:01.528 --> 00:14:05.228
about longitudinal treatment patterns and then, of course,

244
00:14:05.328 --> 00:14:09.208
reproducible real-world endpoints like overall survival and progression-free

245
00:14:09.268 --> 00:14:09.708
survival.

246
00:14:11.388 --> 00:14:14.448
We considered existing strong foundations

247
00:14:15.348 --> 00:14:18.348
for informing how we wanted to construct the data model.

248
00:14:19.068 --> 00:14:22.288
So for instance, we looked to FHIR and

249
00:14:22.348 --> 00:14:25.508
mCODE for interoperability

250
00:14:25.688 --> 00:14:29.148
components, and then also the

