00:58:44.628 --> 00:58:48.428
started last year. CANDLE stands for National Cancer Data

1017
00:58:48.548 --> 00:58:51.348
Node Developers, and it's coordinated by

1018
00:58:51.408 --> 00:58:54.988
Health-RI in the Netherlands, and it

1019
00:58:55.068 --> 00:58:58.748
basically unifies 40 partners around 20

1020
00:58:58.788 --> 00:59:02.208
countries in Europe, as you can see on the right-hand side.

1021
00:59:02.308 --> 00:59:05.608
These national cancer nodes are either coming from the various

1022
00:59:05.828 --> 00:59:08.988
institutions, a couple of them are shown on the bottom right,

1023
00:59:09.708 --> 00:59:13.188
or they are managed through the health ministry of the countries themselves.

1024
00:59:13.417 --> 00:59:17.068
And the idea of CANDLE is to generate national hubs for

1025
00:59:17.128 --> 00:59:21.028
harmonizing data to connect these clinical genomics and

1026
00:59:21.068 --> 00:59:24.988
molecular imaging data to provide tools and fair research data sets.

1027
00:59:25.488 --> 00:59:28.628
And CANDLE itself is then embedded in even higher structure, the

1028
00:59:28.668 --> 00:59:32.288
Oncan and the European Cancer Patient Digital Centers.

1029
00:59:33.418 --> 00:59:37.188
The Oncan Connect project, which also started last year,

1030
00:59:37.528 --> 00:59:41.128
means understanding cancer. It is now the idea that the

1031
00:59:41.268 --> 00:59:44.968
national cancer nodes put all of the data in this federated

1032
00:59:45.068 --> 00:59:48.848
service, connecting all of these national data, and

1033
00:59:48.908 --> 00:59:52.588
then we can have cross-country queries in federated

1034
00:59:53.468 --> 00:59:54.008
research.

1035
00:59:55.248 --> 00:59:58.848
Oncan is also then accompanied by the EU

1036
00:59:59.128 --> 01:00:02.668
Cancer Information Portal. That is the idea that you

1037
01:00:04.108 --> 01:00:07.268
want to empower patients and improve health literacy.

1038
01:00:07.748 --> 01:00:11.408
So we have the medical guidelines, patient outcomes, and evidence-based

1039
01:00:11.448 --> 01:00:14.688
resources, take AI quality control, and then build a

1040
01:00:14.748 --> 01:00:18.368
library that allows patients to inform themselves about prevention,

1041
01:00:18.428 --> 01:00:20.348
diagnosis, and treatment.

1042
01:00:21.268 --> 01:00:25.128
So basically having patient empowerment, having federated data access.

1043
01:00:25.628 --> 01:00:28.628
This is now the grand scheme, how we can

1044
01:00:29.268 --> 01:00:31.228
create precision oncology in the EU.

1045
01:00:31.688 --> 01:00:34.308
So you have the data users per country.

1046
01:00:34.618 --> 01:00:38.448
You have the CANDLE national cancer nodes, and they should build

1047
01:00:38.528 --> 01:00:40.668
then European health data space,

1048
01:00:42.008 --> 01:00:45.808
secure data models, and this then integrates together with the

1049
01:00:45.848 --> 01:00:49.688
Oncan and EU-CIP platforms to reduce the burden of cancer in

1050
01:00:49.728 --> 01:00:53.388
Europe. So this is what is currently ongoing.

1051
01:00:53.468 --> 01:00:57.352
Now-Of course, on the national level, there

1052
01:00:57.392 --> 01:00:58.472
have also been

1053
01:00:59.432 --> 01:01:02.882
projects that really try to bring precision oncology

1054
01:01:02.932 --> 01:01:06.252
into healthcare. And one of these interesting model projects

1055
01:01:06.852 --> 01:01:10.652
in Germany is GenomeDE. It's a model

1056
01:01:10.752 --> 01:01:14.412
project for genome sequencing for rare genetic

1057
01:01:14.472 --> 01:01:18.412
diseases and cancer, and it wants to bring precision medicine in

1058
01:01:18.452 --> 01:01:20.932
the clinical routine and certified hospitals.

1059
01:01:21.312 --> 01:01:23.032
So 27 hospitals across

1060
01:01:24.372 --> 01:01:28.182
Germany, as shown here on the right, are allowed to sequence patients,

1061
01:01:28.252 --> 01:01:32.152
whole exome, whole genome sequencing, and from that derive

1062
01:01:32.972 --> 01:01:35.032
special or individual treatments.

1063
01:01:35.392 --> 01:01:38.952
It started in 2019, and last year in '25, the first

1064
01:01:39.052 --> 01:01:42.652
patients were enrolled. And the interesting fact is that the health insurance

1065
01:01:42.852 --> 01:01:46.112
basically pay for this sequencing, and they pay for the

1066
01:01:46.172 --> 01:01:49.852
sequencing if the data

1067
01:01:49.992 --> 01:01:53.502
per patient is uploaded into genome data centers.

1068
01:01:53.992 --> 01:01:57.332
And actually, it was the Genie data model, which

1069
01:01:57.792 --> 01:02:01.732
basically was a blueprint for the data that has to be uploaded to the data

1070
01:02:01.812 --> 01:02:05.452
center here. Plus, additionally, you have to upload patient

1071
01:02:05.532 --> 01:02:06.802
consent, reimbursement

1072
01:02:08.272 --> 01:02:12.032
information, and therapy recommendation, and this data upload is mandatory.

1073
01:02:12.432 --> 01:02:14.592
That means that

1074
01:02:15.472 --> 01:02:19.352
in this model scheme of the GenomeDE, you get money for data.

1075
01:02:19.772 --> 01:02:22.652
So you get around

1076
01:02:23.852 --> 01:02:27.732
7.5 or 8.5k euros per

1077
01:02:28.152 --> 01:02:31.452
patient sequencing, depending you do exome or whole genome sequencing,

1078
01:02:32.032 --> 01:02:35.572
and the number of patient money you get per year is capped.

1079
01:02:35.582 --> 01:02:38.792
So in our hospital, we get roughly 3 million euros per year.

1080
01:02:39.392 --> 01:02:42.032
And it works like this, that if the patient enters the hospital,

1081
01:02:43.472 --> 01:02:47.372
they're sequenced, and the therapy recommendation is finished.

1082
01:02:47.632 --> 01:02:50.872
Then you upload the clinical data and the genomic data to the

1083
01:02:50.892 --> 01:02:54.372
respective data nodes. The data nodes do quality

1084
01:02:54.432 --> 01:02:58.292
control, check whether the data is there or the variables have been filled in,

1085
01:02:58.632 --> 01:03:02.552
and then they return a confirmation token, and only when this confirmation

1086
01:03:02.592 --> 01:03:05.612
token has been returned, health insurance will pay.

1087
01:03:06.112 --> 01:03:08.452
So this is actually a very good way to enlarge

1088
01:03:09.652 --> 01:03:10.552
your data sets

1089
01:03:11.532 --> 01:03:15.392
with precision oncology data, which you can then use later

1090
01:03:15.512 --> 01:03:19.172
on for research. And the vision for this project is to

1091
01:03:19.212 --> 01:03:22.252
connect it to the national data nodes and the European health data space.

1092
01:03:22.692 --> 01:03:26.332
Because, as I can say, the data implementation at this,

1093
01:03:26.992 --> 01:03:30.852
as right now, still needs a lot of work in this

1094
01:03:30.872 --> 01:03:34.832
research perspective. How this actually will work in the end, and the data

1095
01:03:34.892 --> 01:03:38.272
format that can be exported has not been fixed yet.

1096
01:03:38.712 --> 01:03:42.472
So a lot of work ahead. The last project I want to talk

1097
01:03:42.552 --> 01:03:44.992
about is basically Genie with a twist.

1098
01:03:45.792 --> 01:03:49.332
So the German Medical Informatics Initiative that tried to

1099
01:03:49.532 --> 01:03:53.232
structure clinical data also had a use case for molecular tumor

1100
01:03:53.252 --> 01:03:56.572
boards, which sequenced cancer patients for individual therapy.

1101
01:03:57.032 --> 01:03:59.912
And the question there was: how can we standardize workflows?

1102
01:03:59.992 --> 01:04:00.492
How can we

1103
01:04:01.312 --> 01:04:05.152
develop a tool that can visualize large data, is compliant with open

1104
01:04:05.232 --> 01:04:07.092
standards, and integrates into hospital IT?

1105
01:04:07.572 --> 01:04:11.312
And the choice was basically to use cBioPortal from the

1106
01:04:11.332 --> 01:04:13.752
Genie Project and adapt it to molecular tumor boards.

1107
01:04:15.072 --> 01:04:16.792
And as such,

1108
01:04:17.772 --> 01:04:21.212
we now have enlarged the cBioPortal

1109
01:04:21.632 --> 01:04:25.492
for molecular tumor boards and patient care that we take

1110
01:04:25.592 --> 01:04:26.432
the grant

1111
01:04:27.552 --> 01:04:31.172
method that we can-- or this visualization of patient history and clinical data,

1112
01:04:31.232 --> 01:04:35.112
the access to the latest database information for variants, for

1113
01:04:35.172 --> 01:04:36.761
case preparation and presentation,

1114
01:04:37.652 --> 01:04:41.512
and then add a tab for structured therapy recommendations.

1115
01:04:41.592 --> 01:04:44.772
So we document this therapy recommendation directly in

1116
01:04:46.492 --> 01:04:50.192
the cBioPortal as a free text and also

1117
01:04:50.732 --> 01:04:54.712
as a structured information for therapy priority, molecular reasoning,

1118
01:04:55.152 --> 01:04:58.912
treatment evidence level, according to OncoKB and the

1119
01:04:58.972 --> 01:05:02.872
literature. For that, we built a FHIR server within cBioPortal

1120
01:05:02.912 --> 01:05:06.472
and have some restful interfaces to communicate with hospital ITs.

1121
01:05:07.152 --> 01:05:11.012
We augmented cBioPortal with clinical trial search that we can

1122
01:05:11.072 --> 01:05:12.872
enroll patients in

1123
01:05:13.872 --> 01:05:15.272
clinical trials if possible,

1124
01:05:16.132 --> 01:05:20.112
and this really proved to be highly efficient to run molecular tumor

1125
01:05:20.132 --> 01:05:24.112
boards, and particularly in clinical care, time is money,

1126
01:05:24.232 --> 01:05:28.192
and you need to be efficient here. And it has been in production for

1127
01:05:28.832 --> 01:05:32.752
four years. We have more than 2,000 cases, and we are trying to roll out

1128
01:05:32.822 --> 01:05:36.612
cBioPortal in the MTB version across Germany within a

1129
01:05:36.652 --> 01:05:38.032
